ARBALEST Molecular Dynamics Package and ARROW forcefield
---------------------------------------------------------

Inputs and running of Molecular Dynamics Simulations
----------------------------------------------------

1) System requirements: 
	There are two linux versions of the binaries: cuda and CPU only. the 
	CPU binary should run on recent UBUNTU systems and other linux flavors. 
	For any problems use the 'issues' in https://github.com/freecurve/solvation_examples repository
	
	Post-processing scripts require MATLAB > R2017

2) Running examples: 
For solute hydration Classical MD simulations

Go to HydrationExamples
Go to MD sub-directory
Three examples of solute hydration a) methane b) water c) benzene
Go to these directories
	a) For MD calculation on CPU
		./run_cpu.sh 
	b) For MD calculation on GPU
		./run_gpu.sh

2) For solute hydration Path-Integral MD simulations

Go to HydrationExamples
Go to PIMD sub-directory
Three examples of solute hydration a) methane b) water c) benzene
        a) For PIMD calculation on CPU
                ./run_cpu.sh
        b) For PIMD calculation on GPU
                ./run_gpu.sh

The PIMD examples will run with 8 beads in H2O and 4 beads in CHEX

3) Post-processing and analysis: 


Helpful notes: 

a) The binaries for cpu and gpu version can be found in BIN:
Arbalest binaries revision 3364

-	ArbalestLight-FloatDoubleFixed-Cuda.r3364
	Cuda 10.2 is required to be installed
	Use '--gpu 1' option to run on GPU
	
-	ArbalestLight-FloatDoubleFixed.r3364
	Runs on CPU only	
	

use --help option to run Arbalest help, e.g.
$./ArbalestLight-FloatDoubleFixed.r3364 --help

Welcome to ARBALEST!
Executable file name: ./ArbalestLight-FloatDoubleFixed.r3364
Command line is: ./ArbalestLight-FloatDoubleFixed.r3364 --help
Allowed options:
  -C [ --config ] arg (=./config.xml) Configuration file
  --log arg (=./Arbalest.log)         Log file name
  --loglevel arg (=2)                 Logging level [0..5]
  --gpu arg (=0)                      Whether to use GPU for simulation
  -I [ --gpudeviceid ] arg (=-1)      Which GPU device should be used for
                                      simulation
  -S [ --gpudevicescript ] arg        Execute this script to define which GPU
                                      device should be used for simulation
  -P [ --mpiprocdelay ] arg (=10)     Delay interval, in sec, between starts of
                                      successive MPI processes. Required for
                                      correct assignment of GPU devices. Works
                                      only when 'gpu' flag is true.
  --gputestinfo arg (=0)              Do output GPU test info files? (test.xml,
                                      mem.xml,meas.xml)
  --gpusynchronize arg (=0)           Turn on synchronization of [all] GPU
                                      kernels with CPU (for correct timings
                                      only)
  --omp arg (=1)                      Number of OpenMP threads
  --verify arg (=0)                   Turn on verification of parallel
                                      DomainController (currently used for GPU
                                      only)
  --outTS arg (=1)                    Whether to write time stamp in output
                                      files names
  -D [ --dumpconfig ] arg (=1)        Whether to dump config file or not
  -M [ --mkdirs ] arg (=1)            Whether to create output directories or
                                      not
  -v [ --version ]                    Print program version
  -h [ --help ]                       Print help message


Floating point precision: single
Always use double in atomwise functions: true
Store coordinates in Fixed Precision: true
Store velocities in Fixed Precision: true
Accumulate forces in Fixed Precision: true
Force initialization method: F(-1) = F(0)
Using OpenMP parallelization: yes
Using FFT library: yes
GPU support: disabled
Version: 0.0.0.3363

b) The atom-typified input files for Methane, Benzene and water (HyperChemformat-HIN) can be found in HIN


